comment-author"><strong><span class="author"><a id="author_t1_28tv" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/gwern/">gwern</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">06 July 2010 09:56:31AM</span><span class="votes " id='score_t1_28tv'>7 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_28tv'] = ['6 points', '7 points', '8 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return hidecomment('t1_28tv')">[-]</a></div><div id="body_t1_28tv" class="comment-content"><div class="md"><blockquote>
  <p>"Perhaps the excellence of aphorisms consists not so much in the expression of some rare or abstruse sentiment, as in the comprehension of some obvious and useful truth in a few words. <br />
  We frequently fall into error and folly, not because the true principles of action are not known, but because, for a time, they are not remembered; and he may therefore be justly numbered among the benefactors of mankind who contracts the great rules of life into short sentences, that may be easily impressed on the memory, and taught by frequent recollection to recur habitually to the mind."</p>
</blockquote>

